snippet.textDisplay: Oh, come on! What a waste! The Dreamliner is a bad design because the rigid wingtips and long, slender wings cause (in certain conditions) extreme shimmy and adverse yaw. I'm saying this from experience and avoid flying on them; the designs of the past are solid and reliable, giving tens of thousands of flight hours for each aircraft without a single fatal incident. Boeing ought to give up while it's ahead and dump these idiotic designers and managers who think they can increase prices $50 per flight per person by adding "folding X" unnecessary crap.
snippet.textOriginal: Oh, come on! What a waste! The Dreamliner is a bad design because the rigid wingtips and long, slender wings cause (in certain conditions) extreme shimmy and adverse yaw. snippet.textDisplay: I know that even the previous generation 777 does a clever pivoting trick with its main landing gear to reduce the chances of a tail strike—a feature which is even more important for the 777-9 which is longer still. But I have never noticed this starting to happen before the nose gear is off the ground, like what happened here. Is this something deliberate and new for the extra long 777-9, or is it just because this particular plane is extremely light, not having an interior installed and being fuelled for a relatively short flight, or do all 777s do this all the time?
snippet.textOriginal: I know that even the previous generation 777 does a clever pivoting trick with its main landing gear to reduce the chances of a tail strike—a feature which is even more important for the 777-9 which is longer still. But I have never noticed this starting to happen *before* the nose gear is off the ground, like what happened here. Is this something deliberate and new for the extra long 777-9, or is it just because this particular plane is extremely light, not having an interior installed and being fuelled for a relatively short flight, or do all 777s do this all the time?
